aborateurs et de se sentir responsabilisés, c\'est très engageant et très motivant ? -  -  -  - Profil recherché -  - Vous pensez être apte à réaliser la mission ? Vous êtes la personne que l\'on recherche ! - Vous pourrez ici décrire dans les détails le type de profil recherché. - À l\'aide des qualités listées sur votre droite, vous pourrez affiner ces paramètres. - Les développeurs pourront alors décider de la pertinence de leur profil avec votre offre. - N\'hésitez pas à faire une description relativement générale et méliorative. - Le but est que le développeur puisse se reconnaître ou avoir envie de devenir cette personne. -  - Ajouter un message personnel et empathique est également une excellente façon de connecter avec le candidat potentiel ☕','1561646095176.0','test-welovedevs','JOB_UNPUBLISHED','test','permanent','asap','nan','3.0','[\'IE10\', \'Heroku\', \'HTML5\']','nan','nan'),(1613,'-LiO_xvebCiMAYyCnAWL','14AHto2NzpZFYmjQzh8FpjXGNpd2','Coder and Kiteboader? Skier? Climber? Surfer? We want you! -  - To understand our broader vision, please first see our Investor Presentation   - Tech Stack  - A summary of our current tech stack is at the end of this post however: - We’re pivoting from native to a web-based product.   - All product so far has been developed through a relationship with a primary advisor (and good friend) Chris Candy and his development company. While his team is available for support, our preference is for someone internal to take leadership on our next iteration. Your background will largely determine our future tech stack.  - Development began before being accepted into two startup incubators and we can now take advantage of extensive credits ($20,000 Google, $5000 AWS, CISCO, etc). For example, we will likely migrate from our dedicated server on Vultr to AWS.   - Role & Opportunity  - We have achieved significant progress outsourcing various components, however we’ve hit bandwidth constraints in leadership. Thus, we’re transitioning from contract work to longer-term equity-incentivized roles.   -    - We’re looking for an ambitious engineer who appreciates the problem we’re trying to solve and wants to build something awesome! This is an opportunity to step in, take ownership on product development, and take\nadvantage of progress achieved so far. We\'ve built a lot of data, relationships, and more! We’re not tied to any current technologies and our future tech stack will largely be determined the person assuming this role. You will work with the below team and benefit from the support of a variety of relationships and partnerships.  - Team, Support  - The roles of the team is briefly outlined in our investor presentation and further info is at https://ripatrip.com/team.\n - Brennan is the founder, having first conceived RipATrip in 2016 and taken it on full-time in March 2018. His story is here.   - Patrick joined in 2019 as a cofounder and is leading database development  - Chris is an advisor; through his company we built our iOS MVP  - Moritz is an advisor and supports us on design, UI, and UX  - Tiffany is an advisor and helps on all things startup and tech related  - Shaun is best described as a superfan an is unofficially supporting as an external CTO (20+ years software development experience).  - Ken is our lead investor and brings over 10 years experience in structuring investments  - Sylvia and her company Strawberry Studio have been engaged for branding and design  - Startup Lisboa is the first/primary incubator we’re supported by, and the location of our office. Through them we benefit from numerous relationship (AWS, Google, etc), 130+ mentors, significant cost subsidization and more (ex- multiple free intern programs & partnerships we have benefited from). They are also behind the largest startup development in the world, HCB.   - Startup Discoveries is a travel and tourism specific accelerator we were recently accepted into that we’ll be participating in July. - Native to Web, Why?  - Longer-term we believe that our optimal product is a native app, however we realize that even if so, the journey doesn’t necessarily begin with native. Initially we planned to launch our MVP on iOS and Android. Rather than code both right away, we opted to release on iOS first, get 100+ downloads, and then take user feedback to make updates for Android.   -    - We hit that target in 6 days and then stopped marketing and social efforts in order to focus on user feedback. Our MVP launch also coincided with us relocating to Startup Lisboa in which we immediately engaged 10+ mentors and fellow entrepreneurs. It became evident that a web version would be make more sense at this stage.  - Quicker product cycles  - Cheaper development  - Increased user functionality - Easier implementation of B2B affiliate programs  - Increased scalability  - Product  - Our next release will be an updated web version of our kitesurf travel MVP (demo here, we removed it in May to minimize undue costs). From there we’ll be adding surfing, skiing/boarding, and hiking (we’ve already developed preliminary databases for these).   -    - In terms of functionality, conceptually the only similar site is https://nomadlist.com/ (click “Add Filters”). We’re hesitant to reference it as the UI and UX could be significantly better in our opinion, and it’s a niche product. However, it’s provides comparable user value in allowing for a very personalized destination search, and it’s been relatively successful despite being niche and operated by one person.  -    - Web mockups will begin in July and will coincide with support from the Travel & Tourism Discoveries Incubator. We expect a minimum of 2-3 rounds of mockups & user-feedback prior to any coding (before our iOS release we had mockups, prototype, and then closed beta).  -    - UI & UX design will draw from successes of Airbnb (which had design inspiration from https://medium.com/). As a UX example, Airbnb rooms has 100+ filters for personalization however it is categorized neatly and not overwhelming (like NomadList). Branding will also be incorporated from Strawberry Studio (currently underway, no professional branding was previously done).   - Location & Compensation  - In our opinion Startup Lisboa is one of the best incubators in the world. Lisbon/Portugal was also chosen for a variety of factors; exceptionally low cost of living and wages among top considerations (average yearly salary <$15K EUR, 4 person dedicated office 200Eur/month, apartment rooms 300Eur/month). As an emerging startup hub it’s tough to beat, and it’s a pretty awesome playground for outdoor sports! We work hard, but we also play hard; Portugal provides a great opportunity for this work/life balance. For non-EU citizens, through Startup Lisboa we have received startup visas that we can allocate, and for non-Portuguese (EU included) residents we’re also approved for the capped 20% personal income tax for 10 years.  -    - Our preference is for a full-time developer in Lisbon but we’re open to a remote and/or freelance role for the right candidate. We’re still very early however and building/fundraising on certain costs assumptions, for example all full-time salaries will initially be capped at $40,000 USD. This makes hiring talent in NA and the rest of Europe more difficult. At time of a Seed or Series A round salaries would be adjusted, but initially equity should be your primary incentive: 5-20% equity is being set aside specifically for this role. We’re currently registering our Delaware C-Corp in advance of our first external funds being received (Brennan has funded/bootstrapped so far).  -    - We’re open to discussing various arrangements; it may not be necessary for a developer to initially join full time. Our web release will still be MVP and we expect an initial build to cost $3-$10K. With current funding we’ve budgeted $20K to get us through a first build and six months of updates and maintenance. In Portugal that gets a full-time developer with 3-5 years’ experience for 6-12 months (2nd cheapest market in Europe), however in NA and the rest of Europe that’s more difficult.  -   - RipATrip Tech Stack  -    - Summary  - Besides the iOS app, all systems are written in Javascript (Typescript). This allows for easy maintenance and collaboration as the languages are the same across platforms. Even the database is in a format that’s similar to Javascript  -    - iOS  - The iOS app was built using the Swift language. Swift is the new standard for all iOS app development. This is essentially the only way to get an app to the app store. We could have gone with Objective-C but it’s a legacy language and Apple is pushing more for the usage of Swift.  -    - Dashboard  - The Dashboard was built using Angular. Angular is built using Typescript which allows the developer to type check before compilation. By being able to type check before compilation reduces the chance of errors and speeds up\nthe development process. The backend was also built using Typescript so having a single language to deal with makes it much easier for any developer to transition between systems.  -    - Angular also gives a nice boilerplate setup with a command line interface which makes it easier to throw together pages rather than building everything from scratch. As for styles and templates, Angular Material (material.angular.io) was used. The Angular Material components are built for Angular and work easily while doing\ndevelopment.  -    - Server  - The API Server was built using NestJS. Typescript can be used in conjunction with NestJS. NestJS is very similar to Angular, but for the backend. It uses a lot of boilerplate templates, in a CLI, that allow any developer to quickly set up routes rather than building them from scratch. Routes can easily be created with a single command and all REST calls can be created within the corresponding route by using a decorator. NestJS also allows for schemas, interfaces, services, etc. This being the MVC design standard across most systems today.  -    - Database  - The database used was MongoDB. MongoDB was chosen because of its reputation for big data performance and also being easier to use,personally, as a document database. Setting up schemas is easy to create because of the use of Javascript. Mongoose was the ORM connecting the API to the DB  -    - Locations of Systems  - Server  - The server is being stored an a VPS through Vultr. The server is running Ubuntu 18.10 and is updated daily. NodeJS and MongoDB services were installed and running the required servers for the API and database. The database\nis backed up daily and stored on the local system incase of any issues that happen. Snapshots\nof the entire system are then taken once a week.  -  - Dashboard  - The Dashboard is stored on heroku as a free service. Considering there is only a single user, at this point, logging in and editing data then there is no point to host the dashboard elsewhere. A heroku account is required to manage the service. The Dashboard is just a simple and basic CRUD system that allows for data manipulation.  -    - Code Storage  - All code is stored through Gitlab in specific repositories for each system.  -    ','1561711706605.0','full-stack-web-developer-ripatrip','JOB_UNPUBLISHED','Kiter, Skier, Surfer, or Climber Remote Full Stack Developer ','freelance','asap','nan','3.0','[\'AngularJS\', \'C\', \'Chrome\', \'Heroku\', \'Gitlab\', \'Github\', \'Java\', \'NodeJS\', \'Slack\', \'Trello\', \'vueJS\', \'Objective C\', \'Matlab\', \'Amazon Web Services\', \'React Native\', \'iOS\', \'Angular\', \'Firebase\', \'Ionic\', \'R\', \'Fullstack\', \'Frontend\', \'Backend\', \'Wordpress\', \'Swift\', \'Typescript\', \'MongoDB\', \'Javascript\']','nan','nan'),(1614,'-LiS5d6SBbm7z1RS02Gb','fltfxMKZ74NobkZB0bMBwUOxLWh1','Mission - Votre mission, si vous l\'acceptez, sera de : -  - Nous recherchons pour un de nos partenaires, une start up, basé à Villeneuve d\'Ascq, 